    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.33-35_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">33</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        411 West 115 St., <hi rend="caps">N.Y.C.</hi>
                        October 14, 1929&#8212;
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>My dear friend,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I am deeply and truly humble this morning; for your beautiful appreciation on Peterson's book was before me when I awoke, How much lies behind this fact: that you could write as you have written; that you are yourself; that you have looked beyond the temporal personality, to those unending lives that lie behind me, as they lie behind you. So the hour strikes, and you have had your say; and all 
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.33-35_0002a"/>
                
                    those who have struggled for me, and for things far greater than myself, bless you. &#8212; What a glory it is to have the privilege of doing a great and beautiful thing &#8212; and <hi rend="underline">to want</hi> to do it, as you have just done!</p>
                
                <p>Peterson will be delighted with the essay.&#8212; He is a splendid, robust fellow, with great courage and honesty. &#8212;His grandfather went across the plains in a covered wagon; his grandmother shot an Indian. &#8212;And Longman will be delighted. &#8212;</p>
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.33-35_0002b"/>
                
                <p>I cannot adequately tell you how happy I am in all you have said; of the anthology itself&#8212; just the right words; of my own work. I shall, however, be eternally grateful. &#8212; I am enclosing thirty cents in stamps for six clippings (do not bother to send the whole paper, but just your article); for I want to share this <add>happiness</add> with my best friends.</p>
                
                <p>I do not need to comment on your words, because you have said <hi rend="underline">perfectly</hi> what I would wish to be said, if it could be true. And you
                
                    <fw type="curatorial">34</fw>
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.33-35_0003"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">35</fw>
                    
                    you have said this, and I <hi rend="underline">trust your words</hi>. Therefore, you have strengthened me with ghostly armor.</p>
                
                <p>I wish I could be with you on high places; but that will be someday.&#8212; But you have been like a clear mountain wind to me, and I shall breathe deeply of it, and press forward.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Gratefully, affectionately Yours</salute>
                
                    <signed>Thomas S Jones Jr.</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <p>What you have said of the <hi rend="underline">personality</hi> of the poet&#8212; like the oak, the pine, the cedar&#8212; is my own approach: but that means <hi rend="underline">vision</hi> and <hi rend="underline">age</hi>.</p>
                </postscript>
                
            </div1>
